```

`super().__str__()`` returns the string representation of the current class `MyClass` in the `__str__()` method of the parent class (`super().__str__()`)`.

So in the end this creates a custom toString method.

If you look at the `__str__()` method you can see this implementation is rather trivial.
It seems that the same trick would not work for custom attributes such as `age`

But this is false.
You can create any custom attribute on a class such as `age` as follows,

```python
class MyClass:
    age = 0
    def __init__(self, data):
        #... Initialisations
    def __str__(self):
        return 'The class was {} with age {}.'.format(super().__str__(), MyClass.age)
```

So this simple example teaches us that you can create the ability to represent any custom attribute of any class in the same way regardless of whether it's a built-in attribute or a custom made one.

